    {
      "content": "Introduction",
      "pos": [
        5226,
        5238
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The fundamental requirements for deploying Windows Server Active Directory on Azure virtual machines differ very little from deploying it in on-premises virtual machines (and, to some extent, physical machines).",
      "pos": [
        5240,
        5451
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, in the case of Windows Server AD DS, if the domain controllers (DCs) that you deploy on Azure virtual machines are replicas in an existing on-premises corporate domain/forest, then the Azure deployment can largely be treated in the same way as you might treat any other additional Windows Server Active Directory site.",
      "pos": [
        5452,
        5783
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That is, subnets must be defined in Windows Server AD DS, a site created, the subnets linked to that site, and connected to other sites using appropriate site-links.",
      "pos": [
        5784,
        5949
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There are, however, some differences that are common to all Azure deployments and some that vary according to the specific deployment scenario.",
      "pos": [
        5950,
        6093
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Two fundamental differences are outlined below:",
      "pos": [
        6094,
        6141
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure virtual machines may need connectivity to the on-premises corporate network.",
      "pos": [
        6147,
        6229
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Connecting Azure virtual machines back to an on-premises corporate network requires Azure virtual network, which includes a site-to-site or site-to-point virtual private network (VPN) component able to seamlessly connect Azure virtual machines and on-premises machines.",
      "pos": [
        6231,
        6500
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This VPN component could also enable on-premises domain member computers to access a Windows Server Active Directory domain whose domain controllers are hosted exclusively on Azure virtual machines.",
      "pos": [
        6501,
        6699
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is important to note, though, that if the VPN fails, authentication and other operations that depend on Windows Server Active Directory will also fail.",
      "pos": [
        6700,
        6854
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While users may be able to sign in using existing cached credentials, all peer-to-peer or client-to-server authentication attempts for which tickets have yet to be issued or have become stale will fail.",
      "pos": [
        6855,
        7057
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        7059,
        7325
      ],
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Network<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/documentation/services/virtual-network/)</ept> for a demonstration video and a list of step-by-step tutorials, including <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Configure a Site-to-Site VPN in the Azure portal<ept id=\"p2\">](../vpn-gateway/vpn-gateway-site-to-site-create.md)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> You can also deploy Windows Server Active Directory on an Azure virtual network that does not have connectivity with an on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        7329,
        7482
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The guidelines in this topic, however, assume that an Azure virtual network is used because it provides IP addressing capabilities that are essential to Windows Server.",
      "pos": [
        7483,
        7651
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Static IP addresses must be configured with Azure PowerShell.",
      "pos": [
        7657,
        7718
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Dynamic addresses are allocated by default, but use the Set-AzureStaticVNetIP cmdlet to assign a static IP address instead.",
      "pos": [
        7720,
        7843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That sets a static IP address that will persist through service healing and VM shutdown/restart.",
      "pos": [
        7844,
        7940
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Static internal IP address for virtual machines<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/blog/static-internal-ip-address-for-virtual-machines/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        7941,
        8099
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8104,
        8153
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_Glossary\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Terms and definitions"
    },
    {
      "content": "The following is a non-exhaustive list of terms for various Azure technologies which will be referenced in this article.",
      "pos": [
        8155,
        8275
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8279,
        8431
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Azure virtual machines<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The IaaS offering in Azure that allows customers to deploy VMs running nearly any traditionally on-premises server workload."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8435,
        8673
      ],
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Azure virtual network<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The networking service in Azure that lets customers create and manage virtual networks in Azure and securely link them to their own on-premises networking infrastructure by using a virtual private network (VPN)."
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Virtual IP address<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: An internet-facing IP address that is not bound to a specific computer or network interface card.",
      "pos": [
        8677,
        8798
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Cloud services are assigned a virtual IP address for receiving network traffic which is redirected to an Azure VM.",
      "pos": [
        8799,
        8913
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A virtual IP address is a property of a cloud-service which can contain one or more Azure virtual machines.",
      "pos": [
        8914,
        9021
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Also note that an Azure virtual network can contain one or more cloud-services.",
      "pos": [
        9022,
        9101
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Virtual IP addresses provide native load-balancing capabilities.",
      "pos": [
        9102,
        9166
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Dynamic IP address<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: This is the IP address that is internal only.",
      "pos": [
        9170,
        9239
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It should be configured as a static IP address (by using the Set-AzureStaticVNetIP cmdlet) for VMs that host the DC/DNS server roles.",
      "pos": [
        9240,
        9373
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Service healing<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>: The process in which Azure automatically returns a service to a running state again after it detects that the service has failed.",
      "pos": [
        9377,
        9527
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Service healing is one of the aspects of Azure that supports availability and resiliency.",
      "pos": [
        9528,
        9617
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While unlikely, the result following a service healing incident for a DC running on a VM is similar to an unplanned reboot, but has a few side-effects:",
      "pos": [
        9618,
        9769
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The virtual network adapter in the VM will change",
      "pos": [
        9774,
        9823
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The MAC address of the virtual network adapter will change",
      "pos": [
        9827,
        9885
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Processor/CPU ID of the VM will change",
      "pos": [
        9889,
        9931
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The IP configuration of the virtual network adapter will not change as long as the VM is attached to a virtual network and the VM’s IP address is static.",
      "pos": [
        9935,
        10088
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "None of these behaviors affect Windows Server Active Directory because it has no dependency on the MAC address or Processor/CPU ID, and all Windows Server Active Directory deployments on Azure are recommended to be run on an Azure virtual network as outlined above.",
      "pos": [
        10091,
        10356
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Is it safe to virtualize Windows Server Active Directory domain controllers?",
      "pos": [
        10361,
        10437
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploying Windows Server Active Directory DCs on Azure virtual machines is subject to the same guidelines as running DCs on-premises in a virtual machine.",
      "pos": [
        10439,
        10593
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Running virtualized DCs is a safe practice as long as guidelines for backing up and restoring DCs are followed.",
      "pos": [
        10594,
        10705
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about constraints and guidelines for running virtualized DCs, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Running Domain Controllers in Hyper-V<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/dd363553)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        10706,
        10881
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Hypervisors provide or trivialize technologies that can cause problems for many distributed systems, including Windows Server Active Directory.",
      "pos": [
        10883,
        11026
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, on a physical server, you can clone a disk or use unsupported methods to roll back the state of a server, including using SANs and so on, but doing that on a physical server is much harder than restoring a virtual machine snapshot in a hypervisor.",
      "pos": [
        11027,
        11287
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure offers functionality that can result in the same undesirable condition.",
      "pos": [
        11288,
        11365
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, you should not copy VHD files of DCs instead of performing regular backups because restoring them can result in a similar situation to using snapshot restore features.",
      "pos": [
        11366,
        11546
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Such rollbacks introduce USN bubbles that can lead to permanently divergent states between DCs.",
      "pos": [
        11548,
        11643
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That can cause issues such as:",
      "pos": [
        11644,
        11674
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Lingering objects",
      "pos": [
        11678,
        11695
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Inconsistent passwords",
      "pos": [
        11698,
        11720
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Inconsistent attribute values",
      "pos": [
        11723,
        11752
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Schema mismatches if the schema master is rolled back",
      "pos": [
        11755,
        11808
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11810,
        12016
      ],
      "content": "For more information about how DCs are impacted, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>USN and USN Rollback<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/virtual_active_directory_domain_controller_virtualization_hyperv.aspx#usn_and_usn_rollback)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Beginning with Windows Server 2012, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>additional safeguards are built in to AD DS<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/hh831734.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        12018,
        12153
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "These safeguards help protect virtualized domain controllers against the aforementioned problems, as long as the underlying hypervisor platform supports VM-GenerationID.",
      "pos": [
        12154,
        12323
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure supports VM-GenerationID, which means that domain controllers that run Windows Server 2012 or later on Azure virtual machines have the additional safeguards.",
      "pos": [
        12324,
        12487
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> You should shut down and restart a VM that runs the domain controller role in Azure within the guest operating system instead of using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Shut Down<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> option in the Azure classic portal.",
      "pos": [
        12491,
        12692
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Today, using the classic portal to shut down a VM causes the VM to be deallocated.",
      "pos": [
        12693,
        12775
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A deallocated VM has the advantage of not incurring charges, but it also resets the VM-GenerationID, which is undesirable for a DC.",
      "pos": [
        12776,
        12907
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When the VM-GenerationID is reset, the invocationID of the AD DS database is also reset, the RID pool is discarded, and SYSVOL is marked as non-authoritative.",
      "pos": [
        12908,
        13066
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Introduction to Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS) Virtualization<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/hh831734.aspx)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Safely Virtualizing DFSR<ept id=\"p2\">](http://blogs.technet.com/b/filecab/archive/2013/04/05/safely-virtualizing-dfsr.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        13067,
        13336
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Why deploy Windows Server AD DS on Azure Virtual Machines?",
      "pos": [
        13341,
        13399
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Many Windows Server AD DS deployment scenarios are well-suited for deployment as VMs on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        13401,
        13495
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, suppose you have a company in Europe that needs to authenticate users in a remote location in Asia.",
      "pos": [
        13496,
        13608
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The company has not previously deployed Windows Server Active Directory DCs in Asia due to the cost to deploy them and limited expertise to manage the servers post-deployment.",
      "pos": [
        13609,
        13784
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a result, authentication requests from Asia are serviced by DCs in Europe with suboptimal results.",
      "pos": [
        13785,
        13886
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, you can deploy a DC on a VM that you have specified must be run within the Azure datacenter in Asia.",
      "pos": [
        13887,
        14001
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Attaching that DC to an Azure virtual network that is connected directly to the remote location will improve authentication performance.",
      "pos": [
        14002,
        14138
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure is also well-suited as a substitute to otherwise costly disaster recovery (DR) sites.",
      "pos": [
        14140,
        14231
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The relatively low-cost of hosting a small number of domain controllers and a single virtual network on Azure represents an attractive alternative.",
      "pos": [
        14232,
        14379
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Finally, you may want to deploy a network application on Azure, such as SharePoint, that requires Windows Server Active Directory but has no dependency on the on-premises network or the corporate Windows Server Active Directory.",
      "pos": [
        14381,
        14609
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, deploying an isolated forest on Azure to meet the SharePoint server’s requirements is optimal.",
      "pos": [
        14610,
        14718
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Again, deploying network applications that do require connectivity to the on-premises network and the corporate Active Directory is also supported.",
      "pos": [
        14719,
        14866
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Since it provides a layer-3 connection, the VPN component that provides connectivity between an Azure virtual network and an on-premises network can also enable member servers that run on-premises to leverage DCs that run as Azure virtual machines on Azure virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        14870,
        15156
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But if the VPN is unavailable, communication between on-premises computers and Azure-based domain controllers will not function, resulting in authentication and various other errors.",
      "pos": [
        15157,
        15339
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Contrasts between deploying Windows Server Active Directory domain controllers on Azure Virtual Machines versus on-premises",
      "pos": [
        15346,
        15469
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For any Windows Server Active Directory deployment scenario that includes more than a single VM, it is necessary to use an Azure virtual network for IP address consistency.",
      "pos": [
        15473,
        15645
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that this guide assumes that DCs are running on an Azure virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        15646,
        15724
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As with on-premises DCs, static IP addresses are recommended.",
      "pos": [
        15728,
        15789
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A static IP address can only be configured by using Azure PowerShell.",
      "pos": [
        15790,
        15859
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Static internal IP address for VMs<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/blog/static-internal-ip-address-for-virtual-machines/)</ept> for more details.",
      "pos": [
        15860,
        16000
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you have monitoring systems or other solutions that check for static IP address configuration within the guest operating system, you can assign the same static IP address to the network adapter properties of the VM.",
      "pos": [
        16001,
        16219
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But be aware that the network adapter will be discarded if the VM undergoes service healing or is shut down in the classic portal and has its address deallocated.",
      "pos": [
        16220,
        16382
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In that case, the static IP address within the guest will need to be reset.",
      "pos": [
        16383,
        16458
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploying VMs on a virtual network does not imply (or require) connectivity back to an on-premises network; the virtual network merely enables that possibility.",
      "pos": [
        16462,
        16622
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You must create a virtual network for private communication between Azure and your on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        16623,
        16726
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to deploy a VPN endpoint on the on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        16727,
        16788
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The VPN is opened from Azure to the on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        16789,
        16845
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Virtual Network Overview<ept id=\"p1\">](../virtual-network/virtual-networks-overview.md)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Configure a Site-to-Site VPN in the Azure Portal<ept id=\"p2\">](../vpn-gateway/vpn-gateway-site-to-site-create.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        16846,
        17054
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        17058,
        17261
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> An option to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>create a point-to-site VPN<ept id=\"p1\">](../vpn-gateway/vpn-gateway-point-to-site-create.md)</ept> is available to connect individual Windows-based computers directly to an Azure virtual network."
    },
    {
      "content": "Regardless of whether you create a virtual network or not, Azure charges for egress traffic but not ingress.",
      "pos": [
        17265,
        17373
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Various Windows Server Active Directory design choices can affect how much egress traffic is generated by a deployment.",
      "pos": [
        17374,
        17493
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, deploying a read-only domain controller (RODC) limits egress traffic because it does not replicate outbound.",
      "pos": [
        17494,
        17615
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But the decision to deploy an RODC needs to be weighed against the need to perform write operations against the DC and the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>compatibility<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc755190)</ept> that applications and services in the site have with RODCs.",
      "pos": [
        17616,
        17862
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about traffic charges, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure pricing at-a-glance<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/pricing/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        17863,
        17976
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "While you have complete control over what server resources to use for VMs on-premises, such as RAM, disk size, and so on, on Azure you must select from a list of preconfigured server sizes.",
      "pos": [
        17980,
        18169
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For a DC, a data disk is needed in addition to the operating system disk in order to store the Windows Server Active Directory database.",
      "pos": [
        18170,
        18306
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Can you deploy Windows Server AD FS on Azure virtual machines?",
      "pos": [
        18311,
        18373
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Yes, you can deploy Windows Server AD FS on Azure virtual machines, and the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>best practices for AD FS deployment<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/dn151324.aspx)</ept> on-premises apply equally to AD FS deployment on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        18375,
        18597
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But some of the best practices such as load balancing and high availability require technologies beyond what AD FS offers itself.",
      "pos": [
        18598,
        18727
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They must be provided by the underlying infrastructure.",
      "pos": [
        18728,
        18783
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Let’s review some of those best practices and see how they can be achieved by using Azure VMs and an Azure virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        18784,
        18907
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Never expose security token service (STS) servers directly to the Internet.",
      "pos": [
        18914,
        18989
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is important because the STS issues security tokens.",
      "pos": [
        18997,
        19054
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a result, STS servers such as AD FS servers should be treated with the same level of protection as a domain controller.",
      "pos": [
        19055,
        19177
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If an STS is compromised, malicious users have the ability to issue access tokens potentially containing claims of their choosing to relying party applications and other STS servers in trusting organizations.",
      "pos": [
        19178,
        19386
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploy Active Directory domain controllers for all user domains in the same network as the AD FS servers.",
      "pos": [
        19393,
        19498
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "AD FS servers use Active Directory Domain Services to authenticate users.",
      "pos": [
        19506,
        19579
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is recommended to deploy domain controllers on the same network as the AD FS servers.",
      "pos": [
        19580,
        19668
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This provides business continuity in case the link between the Azure network and your on-premises network is broken, and enables lower latency and increased performance for logins.",
      "pos": [
        19669,
        19849
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploy multiple AD FS nodes for high availability and balancing the load.",
      "pos": [
        19856,
        19929
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In most cases, the failure of an application that AD FS enables is unacceptable because the applications that require security tokens are often mission critical.",
      "pos": [
        19937,
        20098
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a result, and because AD FS now resides in the critical path to accessing mission critical applications, the AD FS service must be highly available through multiple AD FS proxies and AD FS servers.",
      "pos": [
        20099,
        20299
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To achieve distribution of requests, load balancers are typically deployed in front of both the AD FS Proxies and the AD FS servers.",
      "pos": [
        20300,
        20432
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploy one or more Web Application Proxy nodes for internet access.",
      "pos": [
        20439,
        20506
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When users need to access applications protected by the AD FS service, the AD FS service needs to be available from the internet.",
      "pos": [
        20514,
        20643
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is achieved by deploying the Web Application Proxy service.",
      "pos": [
        20644,
        20708
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is strongly recommended to deploy more than one node for the purposes of high availability and load balancing.",
      "pos": [
        20709,
        20822
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Restrict access from the Web Application Proxy nodes to internal network resources.",
      "pos": [
        20829,
        20912
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To allow external users to access AD FS from the internet, you need to deploy Web Application Proxy nodes (or AD FS Proxy in earlier versions of Windows Server).",
      "pos": [
        20920,
        21081
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Web Application proxy nodes are directly exposed to the Internet.",
      "pos": [
        21082,
        21151
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They are not required to be domain-joined and they only need access to the AD FS servers over TCP ports 443 and 80.",
      "pos": [
        21152,
        21267
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is strongly recommended that communication to all other computers (especially domain controllers) is blocked.",
      "pos": [
        21268,
        21380
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is typically achieved on-premises by means of a DMZ.",
      "pos": [
        21386,
        21443
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Firewalls use a whitelist mode of operation to restrict traffic from the DMZ to the on-premises network (that is, only traffic from the specified IP addresses and over specified ports is allowed, and all other traffic is blocked).",
      "pos": [
        21444,
        21674
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following diagram shows a traditional on-premises AD FS deployment.",
      "pos": [
        21676,
        21747
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Diagram of a traditional on-premises Active Directory Federation Services deployment",
      "pos": [
        21751,
        21835
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, because Azure does not provide native, full-featured firewall capability, other options need to be used to restrict traffic.",
      "pos": [
        21905,
        22038
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following table shows each option and its advantages and disadvantages.",
      "pos": [
        22039,
        22114
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Option",
      "pos": [
        22118,
        22124
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Advantage",
      "pos": [
        22127,
        22136
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Disadvantage",
      "pos": [
        22139,
        22151
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure network ACLs",
      "pos": [
        22195,
        22213
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Less costly and simpler initial configuration",
      "pos": [
        22242,
        22287
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Additional network ACL configuration required if any new VMs are added to the deployment",
      "pos": [
        22290,
        22378
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Barracuda NG firewall",
      "pos": [
        22384,
        22405
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Whitelist mode of operation and it requires no network ACL configuration",
      "pos": [
        22456,
        22528
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Increased cost and complexity for initial setup",
      "pos": [
        22531,
        22578
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The high-level steps to deploy AD FS in this case are as follows:",
      "pos": [
        22582,
        22647
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        22652,
        22855
      ],
      "content": "Create a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>virtual network with cross-premises connectivity<ept id=\"p1\">](../vpn-gateway/vpn-gateway-cross-premises-options.md)</ept>, using either a VPN or <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>ExpressRoute<ept id=\"p2\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/services/expressroute/)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploy domain controllers on the virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        22860,
        22909
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This step is optional but recommended.",
      "pos": [
        22910,
        22948
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploy domain-joined AD FS servers on the virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        22953,
        23011
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        23016,
        23229
      ],
      "content": "Create an <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>internal load balanced set<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/blog/internal-load-balancing/)</ept> that includes the AD FS servers and uses a new private IP address within the virtual network (a dynamic IP address)."
    },
    {
      "content": "Update DNS to create the FQDN to point to the private (dynamic) IP address of the internal load balanced set.",
      "pos": [
        23236,
        23345
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create a cloud service (or a separate virtual network) for the Web Application Proxy nodes.",
      "pos": [
        23350,
        23441
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Deploy the Web Application Proxy nodes in the cloud service or virtual network",
      "pos": [
        23446,
        23524
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create an external load balanced set that includes the Web Application Proxy nodes.",
      "pos": [
        23531,
        23614
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Update the external DNS name (FQDN) to point to the cloud service public IP address (the virtual IP address).",
      "pos": [
        23621,
        23730
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure AD FS proxies to use the FQDN that corresponds to the internal load balanced set for the AD FS servers.",
      "pos": [
        23737,
        23850
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Update claims-based web sites to use the external FQDN for their claims provider.",
      "pos": [
        23857,
        23938
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Restrict access between Web Application Proxy to any machine in the AD FS virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        23943,
        24033
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To restrict traffic, the load-balanced set for the Azure internal load balancer needs to be configured for only traffic to TCP ports 80 and 443, and all other traffic to the internal dynamic IP address of the load balanced set is dropped.",
      "pos": [
        24035,
        24273
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Diagram of ADFS Network ACLs with TCP 443 + 80 permitted.",
      "pos": [
        24277,
        24334
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Traffic to the AD FS servers would be permitted only by the following sources:",
      "pos": [
        24402,
        24480
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The Azure internal load balancer.",
      "pos": [
        24484,
        24517
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The IP address of an administrator on the on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        24520,
        24582
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.WARNING]</ph> The design must prevent Web Application Proxy nodes from reaching any other VMs in the Azure virtual network or any locations on the on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        24586,
        24755
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That can be done by configuring firewall rules in the on-premises appliance for Express Route connections or the VPN device for site-to-site VPN connections.",
      "pos": [
        24756,
        24913
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "A disadvantage to this option is the need to configure the network ACLs for multiple devices, including internal load balancer, the AD FS servers, and any other servers that get added to the virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        24915,
        25122
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If any device is added to the deployment without configuring network ACLs to restrict traffic to it, the entire deployment can be at risk.",
      "pos": [
        25123,
        25261
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the IP addresses of the Web Application Proxy nodes ever change, the network ACLs must be reset (which means the proxies should be configured to use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>static dynamic IP addresses<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/blog/static-internal-ip-address-for-virtual-machines/)</ept>).",
      "pos": [
        25262,
        25527
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ADFS on Azure with network ACLS.",
      "pos": [
        25531,
        25563
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Another option is to use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Barracuda NG Firewall<ept id=\"p1\">](https://www.barracuda.com/products/ngfirewall)</ept> appliance to control traffic between AD FS proxy servers and the AD FS servers.",
      "pos": [
        25632,
        25811
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This option complies with best practices for security and high availability, and requires less administration after the initial setup because the Barracuda NG Firewall appliance provides a whitelist mode of firewall administration and it can be installed directly on an Azure virtual network.",
      "pos": [
        25812,
        26104
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That eliminates the need to configure network ACLs any time a new server is added to the deployment.",
      "pos": [
        26105,
        26205
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But this option adds initial deployment complexity and cost.",
      "pos": [
        26206,
        26266
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, two virtual networks are deployed instead of one.",
      "pos": [
        26268,
        26331
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "We'll call them VNet1 and VNet2.",
      "pos": [
        26332,
        26364
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VNet1 contains the proxies and VNet2 contains the STSs and the network connection back to the corporate network.",
      "pos": [
        26365,
        26477
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VNet1 is therefore physically (albeit virtually) isolated from VNet2 and, in turn, from the corporate network.",
      "pos": [
        26478,
        26588
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VNet1 is then connected to VNet2 using a special tunneling technology known as Transport Independent Network Architecture (TINA).",
      "pos": [
        26589,
        26718
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The TINA tunnel is attached to each of the virtual networks using a Barracuda NG firewall—one Barracuda on each of the virtual networks.",
      "pos": [
        26719,
        26855
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For high-availability, it is recommended that you deploy two Barracudas on each virtual network; one active, the other passive.",
      "pos": [
        26857,
        26984
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They offer extremely rich firewalling capabilities which allow us to mimic the operation of a traditional on-premises DMZ in Azure.",
      "pos": [
        26985,
        27116
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "ADFS on Azure with firewall.",
      "pos": [
        27120,
        27148
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        27226,
        27353
      ],
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>AD FS: Extend a claims-aware on-premises front-end application to the Internet<ept id=\"p1\">](#BKMK_CloudOnlyFed)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "content": "An alternative to AD FS deployment if the goal is Office 365 SSO alone",
      "pos": [
        27359,
        27429
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is another alternative to deploying AD FS altogether if your goal is only to enable sign-in for Office 365.",
      "pos": [
        27431,
        27544
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In that case, you can simply deploy DirSync with password sync on-premises and achieve the same end-result with minimal deployment complexity because this approach does not require AD FS or Azure.",
      "pos": [
        27545,
        27741
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following table compares how the sign-in processes work with and without deploying AD FS.",
      "pos": [
        27743,
        27836
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Office 365 single sign-on using AD FS and DirSync",
      "pos": [
        27840,
        27889
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Office 365 same sign-on using DirSync + Password Sync",
      "pos": [
        27892,
        27945
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "1. The user logs on to a corporate network, and is authenticated to Windows Server Active Directory.",
      "pos": [
        27984,
        28084
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "1. The user logs on to a corporate network, and is authenticated to Windows Server Active Directory.",
      "pos": [
        28087,
        28187
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "2. The user tries to access Office 365 (I am @contoso.com).",
      "pos": [
        28192,
        28251
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "2. The user tries to access Office 365 (I am @contoso.com).",
      "pos": [
        28254,
        28313
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "3. Office 365 redirects the user to Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        28318,
        28363
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "3. Office 365 redirects the user to Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        28366,
        28411
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "4. Since Azure AD can’t authenticate the user and understands there is a trust with AD FS on-premises, it redirects the user to AD FS.",
      "pos": [
        28416,
        28550
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "4. Azure AD can’t accept Kerberos tickets directly and no trust relationship exists so it requests that the user enter credentials.",
      "pos": [
        28553,
        28684
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "5. The user sends a Kerberos ticket to the AD FS STS.",
      "pos": [
        28689,
        28742
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "5. The user enters the same on-premises password, and Azure AD validates them against the user name and password that was synchronized by DirSync.",
      "pos": [
        28745,
        28891
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "6. AD FS transforms the Kerberos ticket to the required token format/claims and redirects the user to Azure AD.",
      "pos": [
        28896,
        29007
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "6. Azure AD redirects the user to Office 365.",
      "pos": [
        29010,
        29055
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "7. The user authenticates to Azure AD (another transformation occurs).",
      "pos": [
        29060,
        29130
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "7. The user can sign in to Office 365 and OWA using the Azure AD token.",
      "pos": [
        29134,
        29205
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "8. Azure AD redirects the user to Office 365.",
      "pos": [
        29210,
        29255
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "9. The user is silently signed on to Office 365.",
      "pos": [
        29263,
        29311
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the Office 365 with DirSync with password sync scenario (no AD FS), single sign-on is replaced by “same sign-on” where “same” simply means that users must re-enter their same on-premises credentials when accessing Office 365.",
      "pos": [
        29318,
        29546
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that this data can be remembered by the user’s browser to help reduce subsequent prompts.",
      "pos": [
        29547,
        29641
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Additional food for thought",
      "pos": [
        29647,
        29674
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you deploy an AD FS proxy on an Azure virtual machine, connectivity to the AD FS servers is needed.",
      "pos": [
        29678,
        29780
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If they are on-premises, it is recommended that you leverage the site-to-site VPN connectivity provided by the virtual network to allow the Web Application Proxy nodes to communicate with their AD FS servers.",
      "pos": [
        29781,
        29989
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you deploy an AD FS server on an Azure virtual machine, connectivity to Windows Server Active Directory domain controllers, Attribute Stores, and Configuration databases is necessary and may also require an ExpressRoute or a site-to-site VPN connection between the Azure virtual network and the on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        29993,
        30311
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Charges are applied to all traffic from Azure virtual machines (egress traffic).",
      "pos": [
        30315,
        30395
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If cost is the driving factor, it is advisable to deploy the Web Application Proxy nodes on Azure, leaving the AD FS servers on-premises.",
      "pos": [
        30396,
        30533
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the AD FS servers are deployed on Azure virtual machines as well, additional costs will be incurred to authenticate on-premises users.",
      "pos": [
        30534,
        30671
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Egress traffic incurs a cost regardless of whether or not it is traversing the ExpressRoute or the VPN site-to-site connection.",
      "pos": [
        30672,
        30799
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you decide to use Azure’s native server load balancing capabilities for high availability of AD FS servers, note that load balancing provides probes that are used to determine the health of the virtual machines within the cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        30803,
        31042
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In the case of Azure virtual machines (as opposed to web or worker roles), a custom probe must be used since the agent that responds to the default probes is not present on Azure virtual machines.",
      "pos": [
        31043,
        31239
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For simplicity, you might use a custom TCP probe — this requires only that a TCP connection (a TCP SYN segment sent and responded to with a TCP SYN ACK segment) be successfully established to determine virtual machine health.",
      "pos": [
        31240,
        31465
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can configure the custom probe to use any TCP port to which your virtual machines are actively listening.",
      "pos": [
        31466,
        31575
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Machines that need to expose the same set of ports directly to the Internet (such as port 80 and 443) cannot share the same cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        31579,
        31730
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is, therefore, recommended that you create a dedicated cloud service for your Windows Server AD FS servers in order to avoid potential overlaps between port requirements for an application and Windows Server AD FS.",
