    {
      "pos": [
        49606,
        49657
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_NetworkTopology\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Network topology"
    },
    {
      "content": "In order to meet the IP address consistency and DNS requirements of Windows Server AD DS, it is necessary to first create an <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure virtual network<ept id=\"p1\">](../virtual-network/virtual-networks-overview.md)</ept> and attach your virtual machines to it.",
      "pos": [
        49659,
        49896
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "During its creation, you must decide whether to optionally extend connectivity to your on-premises corporate network, which transparently connects Azure virtual machines to on-premises machines — this is achieved using traditional VPN technologies and requires that a VPN endpoint be exposed on the edge of the corporate network.",
      "pos": [
        49897,
        50226
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "That is, the VPN is initiated from Azure to the corporate network, not vice-versa.",
      "pos": [
        50227,
        50309
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that additional charges apply when extending a virtual network to your on-premises network beyond the standard charges that apply to each VM.",
      "pos": [
        50311,
        50457
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Specifically, there are charges for CPU time of the Azure Virtual Network gateway and for the egress traffic generated by each VM that communicates with on-premises machines across the VPN.",
      "pos": [
        50458,
        50647
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about network traffic charges, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure pricing at-a-glance<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/pricing/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        50648,
        50769
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        50775,
        50838
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_DeploymentConfig\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>DC deployment configuration"
    },
    {
      "content": "The way you configure the DC depends on the requirements for the service you want to run on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        50840,
        50938
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, you might deploy a new forest, isolated from your own corporate forest, for testing a proof-of-concept, a new application, or some other short term project that requires directory services but not specific access to internal corporate resources.",
      "pos": [
        50939,
        51197
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a benefit, an isolated forest DC does not replicate with on-premises DCs, resulting in less outbound network traffic generated by the system itself, directly reducing costs.",
      "pos": [
        51199,
        51375
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about network traffic charges, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure pricing at-a-glance<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/pricing/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        51376,
        51497
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As another example, suppose you have privacy requirements for a service, but the service depends on access to your internal Windows Server Active Directory.",
      "pos": [
        51499,
        51655
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are allowed to host data for the service in the cloud, you might deploy a new child domain for your internal forest on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        51656,
        51788
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, you can deploy a DC for the new child domain (without the global catalog in order to help address privacy concerns).",
      "pos": [
        51789,
        51919
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This scenario, along with a replica DC deployment, requires a virtual network for connectivity with your on-premises DCs.",
      "pos": [
        51920,
        52041
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you create a new forest, choose whether to use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Active Directory trusts<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc771397)</ept> or <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Federation trusts<ept id=\"p2\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/dd807036)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        52043,
        52238
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Balance the requirements dictated by compatibility, security, compliance, cost, and resiliency.",
      "pos": [
        52239,
        52334
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, to take advantage of <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>selective authentication<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc755844)</ept> you might choose to deploy a new forest on Azure and create a Windows Server Active Directory trust between the on-premises forest and the cloud forest.",
      "pos": [
        52335,
        52596
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the application is claims-aware, however, you might deploy federation trusts instead of Active Directory forest trusts.",
      "pos": [
        52597,
        52719
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Another factor will be the cost to either replicate more data by extending your on-premises Windows Server Active Directory to the cloud or generate more outbound traffic as a result of authentication and query load.",
      "pos": [
        52720,
        52936
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Requirements for availability and fault tolerance also affect your choice.",
      "pos": [
        52938,
        53012
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if the link is interrupted, applications leveraging either a Kerberos trust or a federation trust are all likely entirely broken unless you have deployed sufficient infrastructure on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        53013,
        53215
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Alternative deployment configurations such as replica DCs (writeable or RODCs) increase the likelihood of being able to tolerate link outages.",
      "pos": [
        53216,
        53358
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        53364,
        53443
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_ADSiteTopology\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Windows Server Active Directory site topology"
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to correctly define sites and site links in order to optimize traffic and minimize cost.",
      "pos": [
        53445,
        53542
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Sites, site-links, and subnets affect the replication topology between DCs and the flow of authentication traffic.",
      "pos": [
        53543,
        53657
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Consider the following traffic charges and then deploy and configure DCs according to the requirements of your deployment scenario:",
      "pos": [
        53658,
        53789
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "There is a nominal fee per hour for the gateway itself:",
      "pos": [
        53793,
        53848
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It can be started and stopped as you see fit",
      "pos": [
        53853,
        53897
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If stopped, Azure VMs are isolated from the corporate network",
      "pos": [
        53902,
        53963
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Inbound traffic is free",
      "pos": [
        53967,
        53990
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Outbound traffic is charged, according to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Azure pricing at-a-glance<ept id=\"p1\">](http://azure.microsoft.com/pricing/)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        53994,
        54101
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can optimize site link properties between on-premises sites and the cloud sites as follows:",
      "pos": [
        54102,
        54197
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you are using multiple virtual networks, configure the site-links and their costs appropriately to prevent Windows Server AD DS from prioritizing the Azure site over one that can provide the same levels of service at no charge.",
      "pos": [
        54202,
        54432
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You might also consider disabling the Bridge all site link (BASL) option (which is enabled by default).",
      "pos": [
        54433,
        54536
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This ensures that only directly-connected sites replicate with one another.",
      "pos": [
        54537,
        54612
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DCs in transitively connected sites are no longer able to replicate directly with each other, but must replicate through a common site or sites.",
      "pos": [
        54613,
        54757
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the intermediary sites become unavailable for some reason, replication between DCs in transitively connected sites will not occur even if connectivity between the sites is available.",
      "pos": [
        54758,
        54943
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Finally, where sections of transitive replication behavior remain desirable, create site link bridges that contain the appropriate site-links and sites, such as on-premises, corporate network sites.",
      "pos": [
        54944,
        55142
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configure site link costs<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc794882)</ept> appropriately to avoid unintended traffic.",
      "pos": [
        55147,
        55265
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, if <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Try Next Closest Site<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> setting is enabled, make sure the virtual network sites are not the next closest by increasing the cost associated of the site-link object that connects the Azure site back to the corporate network.",
      "pos": [
        55266,
        55506
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure site link <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>intervals<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc794878)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>schedules<ept id=\"p2\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc816906)</ept> according to consistency requirements and rate of object changes.",
      "pos": [
        55511,
        55720
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Align replication schedule with latency tolerance.",
      "pos": [
        55721,
        55771
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DCs replicate only the last state of a value, so decreasing the replication interval can save costs if there is a sufficient object change rate.",
      "pos": [
        55772,
        55916
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If minimizing costs is a priority, ensure replication is scheduled and change notification is not enabled.",
      "pos": [
        55920,
        56026
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is the default configuration when replicating between sites.",
      "pos": [
        56027,
        56092
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is not important if you are deploying an RODC on a virtual network because the RODC will not replicate any changes outbound.",
      "pos": [
        56093,
        56222
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But if you deploy a writable DC, you should make sure the site link is not configured to replicate updates with unnecessary frequency.",
      "pos": [
        56223,
        56357
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you deploy a global catalog server (GC), make sure that every other site that contains a GC replicates domain partitions from a source DC in a site that is connected with a site-link or site-links that have a lower cost than the GC in the Azure site.",
      "pos": [
        56358,
        56611
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It is possible to further still reduce network traffic generated by replication between sites by changing the replication compression algorithm.",
      "pos": [
        56616,
        56760
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The compression algorithm is controlled by the REG_DWORD registry entry HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\NTDS\\Parameters\\Replicator compression algorithm.",
      "pos": [
        56761,
        56935
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The default value is 3, which correlates to the Xpress Compress algorithm.",
      "pos": [
        56936,
        57010
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can change the value to 2, which changes the algorithm to MSZip.",
      "pos": [
        57011,
        57079
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In most cases, this will increase the compression, but it does so at the expense of CPU utilization.",
      "pos": [
        57080,
        57180
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How Active Directory replication topology works<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc755994)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        57181,
        57305
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        57311,
        57364
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_IPAddressDNS\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>IP addressing and DNS"
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure virtual machines are allocated “DHCP-leased addresses” by default.",
      "pos": [
        57366,
        57438
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Because Azure virtual network dynamic addresses persist with a virtual machine for the lifetime of the virtual machine, the requirements of Windows Server AD DS are met.",
      "pos": [
        57439,
        57608
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a result, when you use a dynamic address on Azure, you are in effect using a static IP address because it is routable for the period of the lease, and the period of the lease is equal to the lifetime of the cloud service.",
      "pos": [
        57610,
        57834
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "However, the dynamic address is deallocated if the VM is shutdown.",
      "pos": [
        57836,
        57902
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To prevent the IP address from being deallocated, you can <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>use Set-AzureStaticVNetIP to assign a static IP address<ept id=\"p1\">](http://social.technet.microsoft.com/wiki/contents/articles/23447.how-to-assign-a-private-static-ip-to-an-azure-vm.aspx)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        57903,
        58139
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For name resolution, deploy your own (or leverage your existing) DNS server infrastructure; Azure-provided DNS does not meet the advanced name resolution needs of Windows Server AD DS.",
      "pos": [
        58141,
        58325
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, it does not support dynamic SRV records, and so on.",
      "pos": [
        58326,
        58390
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Name resolution is a critical configuration item for DCs and domain-joined clients.",
      "pos": [
        58391,
        58474
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "DCs must be capable of registering resource records and resolving other DC’s resource records.",
      "pos": [
        58475,
        58569
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For fault tolerance and performance reasons, it is optimal to install the Windows Server DNS service on the DCs running on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        58570,
        58699
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Then configure the Azure virtual network properties with the name and IP address of the DNS server.",
      "pos": [
        58700,
        58799
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When other VMs on the virtual network start, their DNS client resolver settings will be configured with DNS server as part of the dynamic IP address allocation.",
      "pos": [
        58800,
        58960
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> You cannot join on-premises computers to a Windows Server AD DS Active Directory domain that is hosted on Azure directly over the Internet.",
      "pos": [
        58964,
        59116
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The port requirements for Active Directory and the domain-join operation render it impractical to directly expose the necessary ports and in effect, an entire DC to the Internet.",
      "pos": [
        59117,
        59295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "VMs register their DNS name automatically on startup or when there is a name change.",
      "pos": [
        59297,
        59381
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about this example and another example that shows how to provision the first VM and install AD DS on it, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Install a new Active Directory forest on Microsoft Azure<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-new-forest-virtual-machine.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        59383,
        59620
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information about using Windows PowerShell, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Install Azure PowerShell<ept id=\"p1\">](../powershell-install-configure.md)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Azure Management Cmdlets<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/azure/jj152841)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        59621,
        59823
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        59829,
        59882
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_DistributedDCs\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Geo-distributed DCs"
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure offers advantages when hosting multiple DCs on different virtual networks:",
      "pos": [
        59884,
        59964
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Multi-site fault-tolerance",
      "pos": [
        59968,
        59994
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Physical proximity to branch offices (lower latency)",
      "pos": [
        59998,
        60050
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        60052,
        60267
      ],
      "content": "For information about configuring direct communication between virtual networks, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Configure virtual network to virtual network connectivity<ept id=\"p1\">](../vpn-gateway/virtual-networks-configure-vnet-to-vnet-connection.md)</ept>."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        60273,
        60310
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_RODC\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Read-only DCs"
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to choose whether to deploy read-only or writeable DCs.",
      "pos": [
        60312,
        60376
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You might be inclined to deploy RODCs because you will not have physical control over them, but RODCs are designed to be deployed in locations where their physical security is at risk, such as branch offices.",
      "pos": [
        60377,
        60585
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure does not present the physical security risk of a branch office, but RODCs might still prove to be more cost effective because the features they provide are well-suited to these environments albeit for very different reasons.",
      "pos": [
        60587,
        60817
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, RODCs have no outbound replication and are able to selectively populate secrets (passwords).",
      "pos": [
        60818,
        60923
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the downside, the lack of these secrets might require on-demand outbound traffic to validate them as a user or computer authenticates.",
      "pos": [
        60924,
        61061
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "But secrets can be selectively prepopulated and cached.",
      "pos": [
        61062,
        61117
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "RODCs provide an additional advantage in and around HBI and PII concerns because you can add attributes that contain sensitive data to the RODC filtered attribute set (FAS).",
      "pos": [
        61119,
        61292
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The FAS is a customizable set of attributes that are not replicated to RODCs.",
      "pos": [
        61293,
        61370
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use the FAS as a safeguard in case you are not permitted or do not want to store PII or HBI on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        61371,
        61480
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see [RODC filtered attribute set[(https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc753459)].",
      "pos": [
        61481,
        61586
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Make sure that applications will be compatible with RODCs you plan to use.",
      "pos": [
        61588,
        61662
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Many Windows Server Active Directory-enabled applications work well with RODCs, but some applications can perform inefficiently or fail if they do not have access to a writable DC.",
      "pos": [
        61663,
        61843
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Read-Only DCs application compatibility guide<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc755190)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        61844,
        61966
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        61972,
        62008
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_GC\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Global catalog"
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to choose whether to install a global catalog (GC).",
      "pos": [
        62010,
        62070
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a single domain forest, you should configure all DCs as global catalog servers.",
      "pos": [
        62071,
        62153
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It will not increase costs because there will be no additional replication traffic.",
      "pos": [
        62154,
        62237
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a multidomain forest, GCs are necessary to expand Universal Group memberships during the authentication process.",
      "pos": [
        62239,
        62354
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you do not deploy a GC, workloads on the virtual network that authenticate against a DC on Azure will indirectly generate outbound authentication traffic to query GCs on-premises during each authentication attempt.",
      "pos": [
        62355,
        62572
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The costs associated with GCs are less-predictable because they host every domain (in-part).",
      "pos": [
        62574,
        62666
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the workload hosts an Internet-facing service and authenticates users against Windows Server AD DS, the costs could be completely unpredictable.",
      "pos": [
        62667,
        62814
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To help reduce GC queries outside of the cloud site during authentication, you can <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>enable Universal Group Membership Caching<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/cc816928)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        62815,
        62990
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        62996,
        63048
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_InstallMethod\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Installation method"
    },
    {
      "content": "You need to choose how to install the DCs on the virtual network:",
      "pos": [
        63050,
        63115
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Promote new DCs.",
      "pos": [
        63119,
        63135
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Install a new Active Directory forest on an Azure virtual network<ept id=\"p1\">](active-directory-new-forest-virtual-machine.md)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        63136,
        63278
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Move the VHD of an on-premises virtual DC to the cloud.",
      "pos": [
        63282,
        63337
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, you must ensure that the on-premises virtual DC is “moved,” not “copied” or “cloned.”",
      "pos": [
        63338,
        63437
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use only Azure virtual machines for DCs (as opposed to Azure “web” or “worker” role VMs).",
      "pos": [
        63439,
        63528
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They are durable and durability of state for a DC is required.",
      "pos": [
        63529,
        63591
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Azure virtual machines are designed for workloads such as DCs.",
      "pos": [
        63592,
        63654
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Do not use SYSPREP to deploy or clone DCs.",
      "pos": [
        63656,
        63698
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The ability to clone DCs is only available beginning in Windows Server 2012.",
      "pos": [
        63699,
        63775
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The cloning feature requires support for VMGenerationID in the underlying hypervisor.",
      "pos": [
        63776,
        63861
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Hyper-V in Windows Server 2012 and Azure virtual networks both support VMGenerationID, as do third-party virtualization software vendors.",
      "pos": [
        63862,
        63999
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        64005,
        64089
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_PlaceDB\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Placement of the Windows Server AD DS database and SYSVOL"
    },
    {
      "content": "Select where to locate the Windows Server AD DS database, logs, and SYSVOL.",
      "pos": [
        64091,
        64166
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They must be deployed on Azure Data disks.",
      "pos": [
        64167,
        64209
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        64213,
        64267
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph> Azure Data disks are constrained to 1 TB."
    },
    {
      "content": "Data disk drives do not cache writes by default.",
      "pos": [
        64269,
        64317
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Data disk drives that are attached to a VM use write-through caching.",
      "pos": [
        64318,
        64387
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Write-through caching makes sure the write is committed to durable Azure storage before the transaction is complete from the perspective of the VM’s operating system.",
      "pos": [
        64388,
        64554
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It provides durability, at the expense of slightly slower writes.",
      "pos": [
        64555,
        64620
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is important for Windows Server AD DS because write-behind disk-caching invalidates assumptions made by the DC.",
      "pos": [
        64622,
        64738
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Windows Server AD DS attempts to disable write caching but it is up to the disk IO system to honor it.",
      "pos": [
        64739,
        64841
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Failure to disable write caching may, under certain circumstances, introduce USN rollback resulting in lingering objects and other problems.",
      "pos": [
        64842,
        64982
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "As a best practice for virtual DCs, do the following:",
      "pos": [
        64984,
        65037
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Set the Host Cache Preference setting on the Azure data disk for NONE.",
      "pos": [
        65041,
        65111
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This prevents issues with write caching for AD DS operations.",
      "pos": [
        65112,
        65173
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Store the database, logs, and SYSVOL on the either same data disk or separate data disks.",
      "pos": [
        65177,
        65266
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Typically, this is a separate disk from the disk used for the operating system itself.",
      "pos": [
        65267,
        65353
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The key takeaway is that the Windows Server AD DS database and SYSVOL must not be stored on an Azure Operating System disk type.",
      "pos": [
        65354,
        65482
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, the AD DS installation process installs these components in %systemroot% folder, which is NOT recommended for Azure.",
      "pos": [
        65483,
        65611
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        65617,
        65658
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_BUR\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Backup and restore"
    },
    {
      "content": "Be aware of what is and is not supported for backup and restore of a DC in general, and more specifically, those running in a VM.",
      "pos": [
        65660,
        65789
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Backup and Restore Considerations for Virtualized DCs<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/library/virtual_active_directory_domain_controller_virtualization_hyperv#backup_and_restore_considerations_for_virtualized_domain_controllers)</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        65790,
        66023
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Create system state backups by using only backup software that is specifically aware of backup requirements for Windows Server AD DS, such as Windows Server Backup.",
      "pos": [
        66025,
        66189
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Do not copy or clone VHD files of DCs instead of performing regular backups.",
      "pos": [
        66191,
        66267
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Should a restore ever be required, doing so using cloned or copied VHDs without Windows Server 2012 and a supported hypervisor will introduce USN bubbles.",
      "pos": [
        66268,
        66422
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        66428,
        66491
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_FedSrvConfig\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Federation server configuration"
    },
    {
      "content": "The configuration of Windows Server AD FS federation servers (STSs) depends in part on whether the applications that you want to deploy on Azure need to access resources on your on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        66493,
        66691
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If the applications meet the following criteria, you could deploy the applications in isolation from your on-premises network.",
      "pos": [
        66693,
        66819
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They accept SAML security tokens",
      "pos": [
        66823,
        66855
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They are exposable to the Internet",
      "pos": [
        66859,
        66893
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "They do not access on-premises resources",
      "pos": [
        66897,
        66937
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In this case, configure Windows Server AD FS STSs as follows:",
      "pos": [
        66939,
        67000
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure an isolated single-domain forest on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        67005,
        67057
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Provide federated access to the forest by configuring a Windows Server AD FS federation server farm.",
      "pos": [
        67062,
        67162
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure Windows Server AD FS (federation server farm and federation server proxy farm) in the on-premises forest.",
      "pos": [
        67167,
        67282
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Establish a federation trust relationship between the on-premises and Azure instances of Windows Server AD FS.",
      "pos": [
        67287,
        67397
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "On the other hand, if the applications require access to on-premises resources, you could configure Windows Server AD FS with the application on Azure as follows:",
      "pos": [
        67399,
        67561
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure connectivity between on-premises networks and Azure.",
      "pos": [
        67566,
        67628
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure a Windows Server AD FS federation server farm in the on-premises forest.",
      "pos": [
        67633,
        67715
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Configure a Windows Server AD FS federation server proxy farm on Azure.",
      "pos": [
        67720,
        67791
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This configuration has the advantage of reducing the exposure of on-premises resources, similar to configuring Windows Server AD FS with applications in a perimeter network.",
      "pos": [
        67793,
        67966
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Note that in either scenario, you can establish trusts relationships with more identity providers, if business-to-business collaboration is needed.",
      "pos": [
        67968,
        68115
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        68121,
        68183
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"BKMK_CloudSvcConfig\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>Cloud services configuration"
    },
    {
      "content": "Cloud services are necessary if you want to expose a VM directly to the Internet or to expose an Internet-facing load-balanced application.",
      "pos": [
